text:
New nonprofit formations by year
Each point is the number of organizations receiving IRS tax-exempt rulings that year, across all seven counties — including organizations that have since dissolved. The red line is a five-year moving average. 2026 is a partial year and is excluded. The 2014 spike (467 rulings) is largely administrative: the IRS launched the short-form 1023-EZ application that July and worked through a backlog of reinstatements following the 2011–2012 automatic revocations.

formByYear = {
  const roll = d3.rollups(
    formations.filter(d =&gt; d.ruling_year &gt;= 1960 && d.ruling_year &lt;= 2025),
    v =&gt; d3.sum(v, d =&gt; d.n),
    d =&gt; d.ruling_year
  ).map(([year, n]) =&gt; ({year, n})).sort((a, b) =&gt; a.year - b.year);
  for (let i = 0; i &lt; roll.length; i++) {
    const w = roll.slice(Math.max(0, i - 4), i + 1);
    roll[i].ma5 = d3.mean(w, d =&gt; d.n);
  }
  return roll;
}







Plot.plot({
  height: 380,
  width: 900,
  marginLeft: 50,
  marginBottom: 45,
  style: {fontSize: "13px"},
  x: {label: "Year of IRS ruling", labelAnchor: "center", tickFormat: "d"},
  y: {label: "New organizations", grid: true},
  marks: [
    Plot.lineY(formByYear, {x: "year", y: "n", stroke: GU.s1, strokeWidth: 1.5, curve: "monotone-x"}),
    Plot.dot(formByYear, {x: "year", y: "n", fill: GU.s1, r: 2}),
    Plot.lineY(formByYear, {x: "year", y: "ma5", stroke: GU.red, strokeWidth: 2.5, curve: "monotone-x"}),
    Plot.ruleY([0], {stroke: "#c3c2b7"}),
    Plot.tip(formByYear, Plot.pointerX({
      x: "year",
      y: "n",
      title: d =&gt; `${d.year}\n${fnum(d.n)} new rulings\n5-yr average: ${d3.format(".0f")(d.ma5)}`
    }))
  ]
})







md`&lt;span style="color:${GU.muted}; font-size:0.85rem;"&gt;&lt;span style="color:${GU.s1}"&gt;━&lt;/span&gt; annual rulings &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;span style="color:${GU.red}"&gt;━&lt;/span&gt; 5-year moving average. Hover for values.&lt;/span&gt;`







Source: NCCS Business Master File, all vintages 1989–2026. Rulings before ~1989 appear only if the organization survived into the BMF era, so early decades are undercounted; the recent surge is not an artifact of this.

What kinds of nonprofits are being formed now?
Comparing the category mix of organizations formed since 2015 against the longer-standing sector shows where founders see unmet needs: recent cohorts tilt toward human services and away from the fraternal, membership, and religious organizations that dominate older cohorts.

cohortMix = {
  const active = orgs.filter(d =&gt; d.ruling_year != null && d.subsector_name !== "Unclassified");
  const mk = (rows, cohort) =&gt; {
    const total = rows.length;
    return d3.rollups(rows, v =&gt; v.length, d =&gt; d.subsector_name)
      .map(([subsector, n]) =&gt; ({subsector, cohort, share: n / total * 100, n}));
  };
  return [
    ...mk(active.filter(d =&gt; d.ruling_year &lt; 2015), "Formed before 2015"),
    ...mk(active.filter(d =&gt; d.ruling_year &gt;= 2015), "Formed 2015 or later")
  ];
}







Plot.plot({
  marginLeft: 200,
  marginBottom: 45,
  height: 430,
  width: 900,
  style: {fontSize: "13px"},
  x: {label: "Share of cohort (%)", labelAnchor: "center", grid: true},
  y: {label: null},
  color: {
    legend: true,
    domain: ["Formed before 2015", "Formed 2015 or later"],
    range: [GU.s2, GU.s1]
  },
  marks: [
    Plot.dot(cohortMix, {
      x: "share",
      y: "subsector",
      fill: "cohort",
      r: 6,
      stroke: "#ffffff",
      strokeWidth: 1.5,
      sort: {y: "-x"},
      tip: true,
      title: d =&gt; `${d.cohort}\n${d.subsector}: ${fpct(d.share)} (${fnum(d.n)} orgs)`
    }),
    Plot.ruleX([0], {stroke: "#c3c2b7"})
  ]
})







Active organizations with a classified NTEE category only. Source: NCCS BMF, June 2026 vintage.

Formation trend: is capacity keeping up?
New human-services organizations formed per year across the region, among organizations still active today (IRS ruling dates; dissolved organizations are not counted, so early years understate true formation activity).

hsHist = {
  // formations.csv is aggregated across all categories, so recompute from the
  // active-org file for the human services subset (active orgs only).
  const rows = orgs.filter(d =&gt; hsLetters.has(d.ntee_major) && d.ruling_year &gt;= 1970 && d.ruling_year &lt;= 2025);
  const roll = d3.rollups(rows, v =&gt; v.length, d =&gt; d.ruling_year)
    .map(([year, n]) =&gt; ({year, n}))
    .sort((a, b) =&gt; a.year - b.year);
  for (let i = 0; i &lt; roll.length; i++) {
    const w = roll.slice(Math.max(0, i - 4), i + 1);
    roll[i].ma5 = d3.mean(w, d =&gt; d.n);
  }
  return roll;
}







Plot.plot({
  height: 340,
  width: 900,
  marginLeft: 45,
  marginBottom: 45,
  style: {fontSize: "13px"},
  x: {label: "Year of IRS ruling", labelAnchor: "center", tickFormat: "d"},
  y: {label: "New HS organizations (still active)", grid: true},
  marks: [
    Plot.lineY(hsHist, {x: "year", y: "n", stroke: GU.s1, strokeWidth: 1.5, curve: "monotone-x"}),
    Plot.lineY(hsHist, {x: "year", y: "ma5", stroke: GU.red, strokeWidth: 2.5, curve: "monotone-x"}),
    Plot.ruleY([0], {stroke: "#c3c2b7"}),
    Plot.tip(hsHist, Plot.pointerX({
      x: "year", y: "n",
      title: d =&gt; `${d.year}\n${fnum(d.n)} new HS orgs\n5-yr average: ${d3.format(".1f")(d.ma5)}`
    }))
  ]
})







